HANTAVIRUS UPDATE - AMERICAS (34): CANADA (SASKATCHEWAN)
********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 16 Aug 2013
Source: The Star Phoenix [edited]
http://www.thestarphoenix.com/news/Hantavirus+case+confirmed+Saskatoon+Health+Region/8798389/story.html


Saskatoon Health Region officials have confirmed a case of hantavirus infection in the area. The health region says the patient is under medical care. No other details have been provided. It is the 3rd case recorded by the Saskatchewan Ministry of Health in the last 2 months.

The infection is potentially fatal and can develop after humans are exposed to the hantavirus through the droppings, urine or saliva of rodents such as deer mice [_Peromyscus maniculatus_]. Early symptoms include fever, chills, headache, muscle pain, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, dizziness and respiratory distress.

Saskatoon Health Region deputy medical health officer Shovita Padhi said hantavirus [infection] symptoms are very similar to "run of the mill flu." Symptoms can appear in as little as 3 days after exposure, though the average is 14 days. "Definitely, please be cognizant of these symptoms," said Padhi.

Padhi said those in rural areas, particularly with known deer mice populations, should be especially vigilant. A visit to a family physician will determine whether someone needs to be tested for the virus. If allowed to progress untreated, hantavirus is fatal in roughly 1/3rd of cases.

[byline: Jason Warick]

