[Sporadic cases of hantavirus infections in humans have occurred in Canada's Prairie Provinces and British Columbia for several years. This report does not indicate which hantavirus is involved in this case, but it is likely to be Sin Nombre virus. The circumstances under which the infection occurred are not given.

A US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) site with extensive information about hantaviruses, including those in North America, with clinical signs, treatment, epidemiology, and an image of the deer mouse, _Peromyscus maniculatus_, can be accessed at http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/diseases/hanta/hps/.

The deer mouse is one of the most common and widely distributed mammals in North America. A map showing its distribution can be accessed at http://www.discoverlife.org/nh/tx/Vertebrata/Mammalia/Muridae/Peromyscus/maniculatus/images/Peromyscus_maniculatus_map.320.jpg.html.

Interactive maps of Saskatchewan province can be accessed at http://www.sasksearch.com/travel/sask.htm, and the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/026Y. - Mod.TY]
